iness Innovation Research Program of the National Science Foundation. Drawing on the latest empirical and conceptual research, Innovation and Public Policy surveys the key components of innovation policy and the social returns to innovation investment. It examines mechanisms that can advance the pace of invention and innovative activity, including expanding the research workforce through schooling and immigration policy and funding basic research. It also considers scientific grant systems for funding basic research, including those at institutions like the National Institutes of Health and the National Science Foundation, and investigates the role of entrepreneurship policy and of other institutions that promote an environment conducive to scientific breakthroughs.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aScience and statezUnited States. 0aTechnological innovationsxEconomic aspectszUnited States. 0aTechnological innovationsxGovernment policyzUnited States. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / General.2bisacsh  aInnovation, investment, R&D, tax policy, entrepreneurship, science, venture capital, growth, startups, grant funding.1 aAkcigit, Ufuk, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAzoulay, Pierre, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoolsbee, Austan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHall, Bronwyn H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJones, Benjamin F., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aJones, Benjamin F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKerr, Sari Pekkala, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKerr, William R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLerner, Josh, econtribu